### 2. Compress the painful into the magical

**Founder evidence**

> "Where files come to die. All the data from these files are stored structurally in the Buena app. Yet, Germany's stupid regulations require us to store paper files from our customers physically for 10(!) years. Insanity." — Aug 5

> "At Buena, we're getting rid of all the stupid paperwork property managers have to deal with. These ~40 boxes resemble only ~300 units. Insane." — Jul 17

> "Today I tested how much time a landlord needs to sign a contract with @homeht_. The answer? 1 minute 🤯" — Sep 21

> "Jackie has been working really hard on Buena Accounting for months & the release of the feature led to our property managers saving ~30h per week(!) 🤯" — Feb 2

**What it means.** Din's design taste is benchmarked against pain compression. He gets emotional about workflows that go from "40 boxes of paper" or "30 hours" to a single minute or zero touches. The redesign target isn't "cleaner screen" — it's "the moment a customer says 🤯".

**How to apply at Buena.**
- Maintain a public **Magic Moment Backlog**: a list of the 20 most painful workflows in property management (eviction notices, owner reporting, contractor payouts, deposit settlements, meter readings, AGM voting, vacancy listings) with a target compression ratio for each (e.g., "8 hours → 90 seconds").
- Every redesign brief opens with a single number: the painful baseline (time, clicks, emails, boxes) and the post-redesign target.
- Ship a quarterly "🤯 demo" — three-minute video showing one painful task before vs. after. This is the format Din already uses on Twitter and will instinctively share.

