### 3. Make it 1 of 1 — opinionated by default

**Founder evidence**

> "Our product is 1 of 1." — Jul 23

> "Dino is an n-of-1 founder…" — Apr 21

> "Ambitious, non-consensus, hard working. Three traits that every Project Europe founder I interviewed had in common." — Jul 29

> "Fabian and his team are singular." — Sep 10

> "To build a mediocre product, make a lot of compromises." — Jul 4

**What it means.** Din has explicitly published the formula for mediocrity (compromise) and the formula for greatness (non-consensus, singular, 1-of-1). Generic SaaS patterns — three-pane settings menus, default Material Design components, stock empty states — read as compromises in his frame.

**How to apply at Buena.**
- Refuse to look like a generic vertical SaaS. Replace at least one "default" UI pattern per release cycle with something custom and unmistakably Buena: e.g., the table view for units, the inbox triage flow, the contract preview, the empty state for a new owner.
- Adopt a written **"opinion per screen"** rule: each major screen has one opinionated stance documented (e.g., "We don't show all-time graphs because they bias against new owners"). If a designer can't write the opinion, the screen isn't done.
- Kill the phrase "industry standard" in design reviews. Replace with "what's the Buena answer?"

