### 4. Sweat the micro-details — they are the brand proof

**Founder evidence**

> "I love how the 'Terms' and 'Privacy' links on @capitalxyz's website pop-up when you scroll to the bottom of the page 😍" — Oct 5

> "Index' website today is beautiful. Celebrating a founder like this says a lot. It shows that everyone at the firm genuinely lives their philosophy." — Aug 1

> "All-nighters are fun. 30 minutes before the news broke on our recent round, we published our new website. Team's exhausted, but smiling and happy." — undated (round announcement)

> "Forming taste" — Feb 20

> "Did @dennismuellr & team just drop the best executed seed product launch ever?" — Jan 24

**What it means.** Din's tweets reward execution craft, not just concept. A footer micro-interaction can earn a 27-like public love letter. He notices and remembers. He's also explicit that he is *forming taste* — meaning he expects his design org to keep shipping new evidence.

**How to apply at Buena.**
- Keep a **"Delight Log"**: a shared file where every team member adds one micro-detail per week (toast wording, hover state, loading skeleton, easter egg, sound, micro-animation). Ship at least three per release.
- Build a "polish week" into every quarterly cycle — five days where roadmap is frozen and the only allowed work is detail upgrades. Demo internally at the end.
- Tie redesigns to public moments. Din publishes a website at the same hour as the round announcement; we should plan launches the same way: brand surface, product surface, and storytelling surface ship together, not in sequence.

---

### 5. Speak human — kill the corporate voice

**Founder evidence**

> "I really miss how Steve communicated. It never felt scripted. What is this corporate jibberish? How is anyone supposed to feel inspired by this?" — Jul 31

> "Q: How locked in is the team at Buena? A: Yes" — Apr 11

> "Q: How committed is the team at Buena? @karlvili: Look at my arm" — Mar 26

> "Tenants starting to refer to our buildings & apartments with our brand name always makes me proud (+ they love our homes too)" — Jan 22

**What it means.** Buena's brand voice — already visible in Din's own posts — is direct, dry, sometimes funny, never corporate. Tenants adopting "Buena" as the noun they use for their home is the proof point: brand has crossed into vocabulary. The redesign needs to extend this voice into every word in the product.

**How to apply at Buena.**
- **Voice audit** every customer-facing string: error messages, button labels, empty states, transactional emails, SMS, owner statements, lease addenda. Re-write anything that sounds like it could appear in any other PM SaaS.
- Default voice rules: short sentences, no "kindly", no "please be advised", no passive-corporate constructions, no "An unexpected error occurred". Replace with: "We couldn't reach the bank. Try again, or ping us."
- Tenant + owner emails get the same care as a Twitter post Din would publish. If he wouldn't post it, we don't send it.

