### 6. Industry depth, then leap — earn the right to redesign

**Founder evidence**

> "At Buena, we studied our industry all the way back to 1754 BC and turned what we found into a multi-story exhibition in our offices. Seeing how property management has been an enabler of cities, progress, and capitalism across centuries is what drives us every day." — Mar 13

> "We did this by becoming a property manager. Fast, reliable & an expert in all the things our customers shouldn't have to be." — Jul 23

> "Buena is expanding into banking. Reimagining how properties, homeowners & tenants bank in the future." — Mar 24

> "Driven by intuition, informed by data." — Jul 11

> "Build a beta to generate alpha" — Oct 30

**What it means.** Din respects industry depth. Buena became a property manager itself before redesigning the software for property managers — that's the move he's proud of. Redesign proposals that ignore the operator reality (or worse, propose a "clean" UI that breaks accounting compliance) will not survive him.

**How to apply at Buena.**
- Every redesign brief must include a **History section**: how is this workflow done in 1925, 1985, 2015, today? What are the legal and operational constraints we cannot remove? What can we remove? This is the multi-story exhibition translated into a doc.
- Pair every designer with an internal property manager for a week before they touch a redesign. They should be able to do the job before they redesign it.
- Frame public redesigns as *reimagining*, not *prettifying* — Din's word for the banking expansion is "reimagining." Lift it.

