## Where to Apply It First (suggested order)

1. **Owner Statement.** Highest-frequency, lowest-design-attention surface in the industry. A redesigned monthly statement that an owner *enjoys* opening is a category-defining artifact, and it's mailed/emailed to thousands every month — so brand reach is enormous.
2. **Tenant Portal Onboarding.** This is where "tenants refer to their apartment by our brand name" actually happens or doesn't. First 5 minutes set the tone for the multi-year tenancy.
3. **Property Manager Inbox / Triage.** This is the daily operator screen. If we save 30h/week here the way Buena Accounting did, we get another 🤯 tweet — and a generational moat.
4. **Buena Banking Onboarding.** New product, blank canvas, perfect place to set the new design system in motion before legacy surfaces drag it down.
5. **Buena.com + Careers.** External brand surface. The Index and round-launch tweets prove Din measures the company partly by the website. Ship in the same window as a major product moment.
6. **The Document Layer.** Leases, addenda, notices, owner agreements. Today they are the most paper-y, "files come to die" part of the experience. Make them feel like Buena objects, not legal cruft.

---

## A Note on the Framework's Limits

This framework is reconstructed from a public-tweet corpus, which biases toward what Din chooses to broadcast. Two things it cannot fully capture: (a) the trade-offs he actually makes in private when compliance, accounting accuracy, or operator throughput conflict with design ambition, and (b) the parts of his taste he hasn't yet posted about. Treat the framework as the *direction of his gravity* — not a closed specification. Pressure-test any large bet directly with him before committing the team.
